[1] WHO global update
Date: Mon 14 May 2018
Source: WHO Surveillance and monitoring, influenza updates [edited]
http://www.who.int/influenza/surveillance_monitoring/updates/latest_update_GIP_surveillance/en/


Influenza update - 315 (based on data up to 29 Apr 2018)
--------------------------------------------------------
Information in this report is categorized by influenza transmission zones, which are geographical groups of countries, areas, or territories with similar influenza transmission patterns.

Summary
-------
Influenza activity returned to inter-seasonal levels in most of the countries in the temperate zone of the northern hemisphere except for some countries in Eastern Europe. Activity increased in some countries in tropical America. In the temperate zone of the southern hemisphere, influenza activity increased but remained below the seasonal thresholds. Worldwide, seasonal influenza subtypes A and B accounted for approximately the same proportion of influenza detections.

National Influenza Centres (NICs) and other national influenza laboratories from 107 countries, areas or territories reported data to FluNet for the period from 16 to 29 Apr 2018 (data as of 11 May 2018 03:42:35 UTC). The WHO GISRS [Global Influenza Surveillance and Response System] laboratories tested more than 97 697 specimens during that period of which 9993 were positive for influenza viruses. Among positive viruses, 5605 (56.1 percent) were typed as influenza A and 4388 (43.9 percent) as influenza B. Of the sub-typed influenza A viruses, 1503 (54.6 percent) were influenza A (H1N1)pdm09 and 1252 (45.4 percent) were influenza A (H3N2). Of the characterized B viruses, 428 (84.9 percent) belonged to the B-Yamagata lineage and 76 (15.1 percent) to the B-Victoria lineage.

