- Bahia: H1N1
Date: Tue 15 May 2018
Source: Globo [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://g1.globo.com/ba/bahia/noticia/em-seis-dias-numero-de-casos-de-h1n1-sobe-14-na-bahia-15-mortes-foram-registradas.ghtml


In 6 days, the number of confirmed cases of H1N1 influenza rose from 100 to 114, an increase of 14 percent. The bulletin that updated the data was released by the Health Secretariat of Bahia (Sesab) on [Tue 15 May 2018]

According to the agency, despite the increase of cases, the number of deaths did not increase in relation to the last survey, which was released on [9 May 2018]. Since then, deaths from influenza H1N1 remain at 15.

The bulletin released on Tue 15 May 2018 takes into account the data recorded in the state from January until Sat 12 May 2018. In the same period of 2017, 2 cases of the disease were counted, without deaths.

In 2018, cases of H1N1 influenza were reported in 27 municipalities. The deaths occurred in 6 cities. Salvador recorded 10 deaths. The other municipalities were Camaçari (1); Lauro de Freitas (1); Retirolândia (1); Feira de Santana (1); and Serrinha (1).

The disease has occurred with greater frequency in children younger than 5 tears old and persons older than 60 years. The elderly are the main victims (63.1 percent).

Severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS; SRAG in Portuguese)
---------------------------------
Cases of H1N1 are part of the general reports of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS; SRAG in Portuguese), which accounts for 752 cases and 57 deaths between January and May of this year 2018.

Of the total SRAG cases, 132 were confirmed for influenza, 114 of which were A/H1N1, with 15 of them progressing to death.

In the same period of 2017, 216 cases of SRAG were reported, with 19 deaths. Among them, 20 were confirmed for influenza with no deaths registered; 2 cases of influenza A/H1N1.

Vaccination
-----------
The National Vaccination Campaign against influenza began on 23 Apr [2018] and runs through 1 Jun 2018. In Bahia, the goal is to immunize 90 percent of the target public, made up of 3.6 million people from the priority groups.

These groups are composed of individuals 60 years of age or older; children from 6 months to 5 years; pregnant women and postpartum women (up to 45 days postpartum); healthcare workers; teachers; indigenous people; carriers of chronic non-communicable diseases and other clinical conditions; adolescents and young people from 12 to 21 years of age under socio-educational measures; prison population and prison staff.

--
