- Pernambuco: H1N1 & H3N2
Date: Wed 16 May 2018 16:11 BRT
Source: Pernambuco [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://g1.globo.com/pe/pernambuco/noticia/pe-confirma-mais-tres-mortes-de-pacientes-com-influenza-dois-tinham-h1n1-e-o-terceiro-h3n2.ghtml


The State Department of Health (SES) confirmed on [Wed 16 May 2018], 3 new deaths of patients with influenza virus infection in Pernambuco in 2018. Tests verified the presence of H1N1 virus in 2 patients, in addition to the 3 cases confirmed previously for the same virus. Also confirmed was the 1st death of a person infected with the H3N2 virus this year [2018]. In all, 6 people have died of influenza in 2018.

The epidemiological bulletin released by SES covers the cases recorded from January 2018 until 5 May 2018. In the same period of 2017, there was one death confirmed for influenza [?H1N1], and 5 deaths confirmed for influenza H3N2.

Of the 2 new cases of people dead from H1N1, one was a one-month-old baby, who died on [13 Apr 2018] in Carpina, in the area of Mata Norte of Pernambuco. The other case was that of a 17-year-old girl who died on [18 Apr 2018] in Camaragibe, in Greater Recife.

The 1st death of the year [2018] of a patient infected with the H3N2 influenza virus was a 9-year-old girl, who died on [24 Mar 2018] in Jaboatão dos Guararapes, in the Metropolitan Region.

The confirmation of the deaths occurred one week after SES ratified the 3rd death in the state this year [2018], a 41-year-old man who died in Palmares in the Mata Sul area of Pernambuco, on 2 Apr 2018, and tested positive for H1N1.

He lived in Barreiros, also in the Mata Sul area of Pernambuco, and died at the Palmares Regional Hospital. He was hospitalized on 13 Mar 2018, the same day he had reported severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS; SRAG in Portuguese).

The 2nd death of a patient with H1N1 was that of a 74-year-old woman who died in Jaboatão dos Guararapes, in Greater Recife. The 1st death, confirmed at the end of April [2018], was a 45-year-old man in the Coelhos neighborhood in Recife.

In all, the state has reported 594 cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome. Of these, 22 had positive laboratory results for influenza A/H1N1, 11 for influenza A/H3N2, and one for respiratory syncytial virus (RSV).

Rumors
------
The health secretaries of Recife and Pernambuco denied rumors circulating inn social networks that, by April 2018, 4 people would have died victims of the influenza virus transmitted by the H3N2 subtype in the state.

Vaccination
-----------
In Recife, 170 fixed health posts are open from 8 am to 5 pm to vaccinate patients from the priority groups. According to the Secretariat of Health of Recife, children from 6 months to 5 years old, pregnant women, and women in the postpartum period, have priority for vaccination. Also those older than 60 years and professionals of the public and private education and health networks should be immunized.

Also included in the priority group are persons aged 12 to 21 under socio-educational measures, the population deprived of liberty, prison staff, as well as those with chronic non-communicable diseases and other special clinical conditions, such as cases in which the patient has 2 or more simultaneous diseases.

The vaccination campaign runs until 1 Jun 2018. In Pernambuco, the expectation is to immunize 90 percent of the 2.3 million people that are part of the priority groups.

Prevention tips
---------------
- Wash hands with soap and water often (especially before eating; touching the eyes, nose, and mouth; and after coughing, sneezing, or using the bathroom).
- When coughing or sneezing, cover your nose and mouth with a disposable tissue. After use discard them in trash cans.
- In the absence of a tissue, use the shoulder or inner forearm as a barrier when coughing or sneezing.
- Do not share food, glasses, bottles, towels and personal belongings.
- Keep the rooms ventilated, with doors and windows open, to promote air circulation.
- People with influenza/cold should avoid closed and crowded environments, as well as direct contact with others (hug, kiss, handshakes, etc.).

--
