[The 'SARS' mentioned above refers to the general syndromic reporting of severe respiratory disease and not the viral respiratory disease of zoonotic origin caused by the SARS coronavirus (SARS-CoV). Between November 2002 and July 2003, an outbreak of SARS in southern China caused an eventual 8,098 cases, resulting in 774 deaths reported in 37 countries, with the majority of cases in China (9.6 percent fatality rate) according to the WHO. ("Summary of probable SARS cases with onset of illness from 1 November 2002 to 31 July 2003." World Health Organization (WHO); http://www.who.int/csr/sars/country/table2004_04_21/en/; retrieved 31 Oct 2008). No cases of SARS have been reported worldwide since 2004.- Mod.UBA

ProMED-PORT Mod.RNA commented
"SRAG ("Síndrome Respiratória Aguda Grave" or acute severe respiratory syndrome) is one of the strategies for surveillance of severe cases of influenza in Brazil since the 2009 pandemic. It was previously called DRAG (where "D" meant "doença" or disease) but was changed to SRAG because other viruses [adenovirus, rhinovirus, coronavirus, metapneumovirus, parainfluenza viruses, respiratory syncytial virus] also became targets of virological surveillance beside influenza virus.

In conclusion, all severe respiratory cases, from a surveillance perspective and independent of the primary causative viral agent, are initially reported as SRAG.

In 2018, EW 18 [week of 1 May 2018], in Brazil: 8107 cases of SRAG; 1005 were classified as SRAG by influenza virus; of them, 59.4 percent influenza A(H1N1)pdm09; 8.8 percent influenza A not typed; 11.1 percent influenza B; and 20.7 percent influenza A(H3N2). In 2018, the circulating H3N2 is a seasonal human strain."

